# Worktree workflow

A global shell wrapper (`gwt`) and a standalone script (`cursor-workspace-sync`)
keep the `<repo>.code-workspace` file in step with the live worktree list.
This works in **any git repo** — no Makefile or per-repo setup required.

## One-time install (already done on this machine)

```bash
bash ~/MacM4LocalAgent/scripts/install-worktree-sync.sh
source ~/.zshrc
```

This installs `~/.local/bin/cursor-workspace-sync` and adds the `gwt`
shell function to `~/.zshrc`.

## Creating a worktree

```bash
gwt add .worktrees/<slug> <branch>
# or for a new branch:
gwt add -b <branch> .worktrees/<slug>
```

Example:
```bash
gwt add .worktrees/feat-auth feat/CP-1234-auth
```

This runs `git worktree add` then immediately calls `cursor-workspace-sync`,
which rewrites `<repo>.code-workspace` to include the new folder.

## Removing a worktree (after PR is merged)

```bash
gwt rm .worktrees/<slug>
```

Runs `git worktree remove` then resyncs the workspace file.

## Manual repair

If you ran `git worktree` directly by mistake:

```bash
cursor-workspace-sync
```

## Rules

- Always use `gwt add` / `gwt rm` instead of `git worktree add` / `git worktree remove`
  so the workspace file is never stale.
- Open `<repo>.code-workspace` in Cursor once (File → Open Workspace from File…).
  After that, `gwt` keeps it current with no further editor action.
- Worktrees placed inside the repo (e.g. `.worktrees/`) appear with a relative path.
  External sibling worktrees appear with their absolute path. Both work fine in Cursor.
